<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="44" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1354,1954]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">
<taxonomicName box="[197,320,1355,1379]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Parallygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[197,320,1355,1379]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">Parallygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been assigned to the tribe 
<taxonomicName box="[658,781,1354,1378]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Athysanini">Athysanini</taxonomicName>
(Metcalf, 
<number box="[897,956,1354,1378]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" value="1957.0">1957</number>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Oman" box="[967,1160,1354,1379]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" refString="Oman, P. W., Knight, W. J. &amp; Nielson, M. W. (1990) Leafhoppers (Cicdellidae): a bibliography, generic check-list and index to the World literature 1956 - 1985. C. A. B. International Institute of Entomology 368 pp." type="book chapter" year="1990">
<collectingCountry box="[967,1036,1354,1378]" name="Oman" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">Oman</collectingCountry>
<emphasis box="[1042,1097,1355,1379]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[1103,1160,1354,1378]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" value="1990.0">1990</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) but it differs from other genera of this tribe, including 
<emphasis box="[500,750,1391,1415]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">
<taxonomicName box="[500,622,1391,1415]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Capoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Capoideus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[636,750,1391,1415]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Platyretus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Platyretus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[810,992,1391,1415]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoidophyes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[810,992,1391,1415]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">Scaphoidophyes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in having paired aedeagal shafts with two gonopores, the most distinctive feature of the tribe 
<taxonomicName box="[785,868,1426,1450]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Opsiini">Opsiini</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Emeljanov" box="[883,1081,1426,1450]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" refString="Emeljanov, A. F. (1962) New tribes of leafhoppers of the subfamily Euscelinae (Auchenorrhyncha, Cicadellidae) Entomologicheskoe Obozrenie (Moscow) 40, 120 - 130." type="journal article" year="1962">
Emeljanov, 
<number box="[1021,1081,1426,1450]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" value="1962.0">1962</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Recent phylogenetic analyses have failed to support consistently the monophyly of 
<taxonomicName box="[755,838,1463,1487]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Opsiini">Opsiini</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[894,1020,1463,1487]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Athysanini">Athysanini</taxonomicName>
, (
<bibRefCitation author="Zahniser" box="[1039,1361,1463,1487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" refString="Zahniser, J. N. &amp; Dietrich C. H. (2008) Phylogeny of the leafhopper subfamily Deltocephalinae (Insecta: Auchenorrhyncha: Cicadellidae) and related subfamilies based on morphology. Systematics and Biodiversity, 6, 1 - 24" type="journal article" year="2008">Zahniser and Dietrich, 2008</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Zahniser" box="[1373,1432,1463,1487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" refString="Zahniser, J. N. &amp; Dietrich C. H. (2010) Phylogeny of the leafhopper subfamily Deltocephalinae (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae) based on molecular and morphological data with a revised family-group classification. Systematic Entomology, 35, 489 - 511" type="journal article" year="2010">2010</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dai" box="[151,329,1498,1523]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" refString="Dai, W., Dietrich, C. H. &amp; Zhang, Y. L. (2011) Review of the Oriental leafhopper genus Lampridius Distant (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae: Deltocephalinae), with description of a related new genus. Zoological Science, 28 (5), 380 - 387." type="journal article" year="2011">
Dai 
<emphasis box="[199,248,1499,1523]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">et al</emphasis>
., 
<number box="[270,329,1498,1522]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), but this could be due to a lack of sufficiently informative data and/or low taxon sampling. Moreover, closely related species of some groups vary for certain characters thought to be stable at the tribal level. For example, connectives among species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Ishihara" authorityName="Ishihara" box="[615,925,1570,1595]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Paralaevicephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[615,825,1571,1595]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">Paralaevicephalus</emphasis>
Ishihara
</taxonomicName>
(deltocephaline tribe 
<taxonomicName box="[1178,1311,1570,1594]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Paralimnini">Paralimnini</taxonomicName>
) are either racquet-shaped, as is usual for 
<taxonomicName box="[503,637,1607,1631]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Paralimnini">Paralimnini</taxonomicName>
, or Y-shaped (
<bibRefCitation author="Xing" box="[801,1000,1607,1631]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" refString="Xing, J., Dai, R. H. &amp; Li, Z. Z. (2009) A taxonomic study of the genus Paralaevicephalus Ishihara (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae: Deltocephalinae), with description of four new species from China. Zootaxa, 1979, 53 - 61." type="journal article" year="2009">
Xing 
<emphasis box="[868,918,1607,1631]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">et al</emphasis>
., 
<number box="[940,1000,1607,1631]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" value="2009.0">2009</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), which would cause these congeneric species to key out to different tribes. Similarly, the genus 
<emphasis box="[789,966,1643,1667]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">Paralampridius</emphasis>
Dai, Dietrich &amp; Zhang, closely resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Distant" authorityName="Distant" box="[151,372,1679,1703]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Lampridius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,280,1679,1703]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">Lampridius</emphasis>
Distant
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[390,476,1679,1703]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Opsiini">Opsiini</taxonomicName>
) but lacks the main diagnostic feature of 
<taxonomicName box="[968,1055,1679,1703]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Opsiini">Opsiini</taxonomicName>
: paired aedeagal shafts with two gonopores (
<bibRefCitation author="Dai" box="[283,462,1714,1739]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" refString="Dai, W., Dietrich, C. H. &amp; Zhang, Y. L. (2011) Review of the Oriental leafhopper genus Lampridius Distant (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae: Deltocephalinae), with description of a related new genus. Zoological Science, 28 (5), 380 - 387." type="journal article" year="2011">
Dai 
<emphasis box="[332,381,1715,1739]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">et al</emphasis>
., 
<number box="[403,462,1714,1738]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Also, the paired aedeagi among 
<taxonomicName box="[843,1025,1714,1738]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Deltocephalinae">Deltocephalinae</taxonomicName>
are also found in the genera 
<taxonomicName authority="Dlabola and Japananaus Ball" authorityName="Dlabola and Japananaus Ball" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Masiripius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">Masiripius</emphasis>
Dlabola and 
<emphasis box="[353,488,1752,1775]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">Japananaus</emphasis>
Ball
</taxonomicName>
of the tribe 
<taxonomicName box="[688,844,1751,1775]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Scaphytopiini">Scaphytopiini</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Oman" box="[860,1070,1751,1775]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" refString="Oman, P. W., Knight, W. J. &amp; Nielson, M. W. (1990) Leafhoppers (Cicdellidae): a bibliography, generic check-list and index to the World literature 1956 - 1985. C. A. B. International Institute of Entomology 368 pp." type="book chapter" year="1990">
<collectingCountry box="[860,930,1751,1775]" name="Oman" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">Oman</collectingCountry>
<emphasis box="[940,991,1751,1775]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">et al</emphasis>
., 
<number box="[1013,1070,1751,1775]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" value="1990.0">1990</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) and in some Mukariini. So the tribal placement of 
<taxonomicName box="[379,502,1787,1811]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Parallygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[379,502,1787,1811]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">Parallygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
remains uncertain and is only tentatively retained in 
<taxonomicName box="[1126,1249,1786,1810]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Athysanini">Athysanini</taxonomicName>
pending further studies on 
<taxonomicName box="[270,452,1823,1847]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Deltocephalinae">Deltocephalinae</taxonomicName>
classification.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1354,1954]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">
In addition to the five species dealt with below there are at least three more species represented only by females collected from 
<collectingCountry box="[320,378,1895,1919]" name="India" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">India</collectingCountry>
(
<collectionCode box="[393,474,1895,1919]" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/yr7i-jnjm" name="University of Agricultural Sciences" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">UASB</collectionCode>
). Female genitalia of one of them are illustrated in 
<figureCitation box="[1043,1112,1895,1919]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1195,1218]" captionTargetBox="[229,1370,226,1125]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[181,1405,193,1174]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Female ovipositor of undetermined species of Parallygus. A. First pair of valvula, lateral view; B. First pair of valvula showing distribution of sculpturing; C. Details of sculpturing of first pair of valvula in middle region; D. Details of sculpturing of first pair of valvula in the apical region; E. Second pair of valvula, lateral view. F. Second pair of valvula showing arrangement of teeth." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210585/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">
Figs 
<number box="[1099,1112,1895,1919]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A–F. The distributions of the four species in the Indian subcontinent and 
<collectingCountry box="[638,705,1930,1954]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">China</collectingCountry>
are shown in 
<figureCitation box="[862,930,1930,1954]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1587,1610]" captionTargetBox="[154,1432,193,1565]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[154,1433,193,1566]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 8. Map showing distribution of species of Parallygus in India, Sri Lanka and China." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210591/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="44">
Fig. 
<number box="[914,930,1930,1954]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
